<solution id="eip-133">
  <para id="eip-462"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>490</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>, polystyrene
  </para></solution>
</exercise><exercise id="fs-id1417160" type="problems-exercises">
            <problem id="fs-id1692032">
            <para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="import-auto-id1717955">In what substance in <link target-id="eip-69"/> is the speed of light <span><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>290</m:mtext><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>8</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> m/s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math>? </span></para></problem>
        </exercise>
        <exercise id="fs-id2074758" type="problems-exercises">
            <problem id="fs-id2156826">
                <para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="import-auto-id1578002">There was a major collision of an asteroid with the Moon in medieval times. It was described by monks at Canterbury Cathedral in England as a red glow on and around the Moon. How long after the asteroid hit the Moon, which is <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>84</m:mtext><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mtext>10</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> km</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> away, would the light first arrive on Earth?</para></problem>
            <solution id="fs-id1478168">
                <para xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="import-auto-id1556318"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>28 s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></para></solution>
            </exercise>
        <exercise id="fs-id2139454" type="problems-exercises">
